Obclig. (June, July, August)
The gonosomes are several times as large as the hydranths.
examine specimens and see if they are located at random along the
stalks, or in regular places.
An Ubelia gonosome has an enlarged transparent covering, the
gonangium, with a blastostyle extending thru it from base to tip.
The outer end, or tip, of the blastostyle expands to make a loose
plug for the gonangium.when mature.
Gn the blastostyle are borne the cluster of gonophores. These
mature as medusae and break loose, escaping past the blastostyle
plug thru the opening of the gonangium. Their free-swimming life
lasts l-2 months. They are commonly caught in tow nets.
See if you can tell which of the gonophores on a blastostyle
the older. Determine the general structure and position of the
tentacles on one of the older gonephores; 
9.196
with needles open the gonangium of a well-matured gonoseme and
examine the gonophores that are relaesed. If any are practically
mature they may show swimming movements. Some that show earlier
stages of development may be liberated by teasing and studied.
If Obelia colonies are kept overnight in a dish of sea water
on the desk (remember not to crowd them), mature swimming medusae can
usually be found in it next day. Examine some of them when available
and note that their structure is imperfect (compared with
that of Bougainvillea).
The velum is reduced to a narrow and somewhat lobed membrane
near the bases of the tentacles. This makes possible an eversion
of the bell when the medusa comes to rest, so that the manubrium
sticks out from the center of the convex side, like the handle of
a post~hurricane umbrella. Watch the swimming movements, and see
how this happens. ln the everted condition, the manubrium is still
morphologically sub~umbrella, though the term has lost its appro-
priateness.
The medusa of Obelia geniculata has 24 tentacles when
liberated, while that of Obelia commissuralis has 16. Beth forms
may be available in the laboratory. Neither has the gonads developed
when liberated.

Gonephores bud off singly around lower portion of the
hydranth. They form reduced medusae with rudimentary
tuft-like tentacles. Before opening out as transparent bell-shaped
forms they suggest cocoanuts. A single colony bears gonophores
of one sex only, but in the living individuals, sex can bc diagnosed
only with difficulty until they mature, when the pinkness of eggs and
